The regular expression you provided is designed to remove markdown-style hyperlinks from a string, leaving only the plain text. If you want to keep the content inside the parentheses `(.*?)`, you can modify the regular expression to capture that content and include it in the replacement string. Here's an example in JavaScript:

```javascript
const input = "Hello, check out this [example](http://www.example.com/).";
const regex = /\[(.*?)\]\((.*?)\)/gi;
const output = input.replace(regex, "$1 ($2)");
console.log(output);
// Output: "Hello, check out this example (http://www.example.com/)."
```

In this example, `$1` refers to the content inside the square brackets `(.*?)`, and `$2` refers to the content inside the parentheses `(.*?)`. The replacement string `"$1 ($2)"` keeps the link text followed by the URL inside parentheses.

If you want to keep just the URL `(.*?)`, you can use the following code:

```javascript
const input = "Hello, check out this [example](http://www.example.com/).";
const regex = /\[(.*?)\]\((.*?)\)/gi;
const output = input.replace(regex, "$2");
console.log(output);
// Output: "Hello, check out this http://www.example.com/ ."
```

In this example, `$2` refers to the content inside the parentheses `(.*?)`. The replacement string `"$2"` keeps only the URL in the output.
